Prabbal Frank attempts to make a subtle distinction between management and manipulation: <cite class="citation book" about="#mwt15" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book\n","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last1":{"wt":"Frank"},"first1":{"wt":"Prabbal"},"year":{"wt":"2007"},"title":{"wt":"People Manipulation: A Positive Approach"},"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/books?id=H9n2vQ7JFVwC"},"edition":{"wt":"2"},"location":{"wt":"New Delhi"},"publisher":{"wt":"Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd"},"publication-date":{"wt":"2009"},"pages":{"wt":"3–7"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-81-207-4352-6"},"accessdate":{"wt":"2015-09-05"},"quote":{"wt":"There is a difference between management and manipulation. The difference is thin [...] If management is handling, then manipulation is skilful handling. In short, manipulation is skilful management. [...] Manipulation is in essence leveraged management. [...] It is an alive thing while management is a dead concept. It requires a proactive approach rather than a reactive approach. [...] People cannot be managed."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAhk">Frank, Prabbal (2007). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=H9n2vQ7JFVwC" id="mwAho"><i id="mwAhs">People Manipulation: A Positive Approach</i></a> (2 ed.). New Delhi: Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd (published 2009). pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAhw"> </span>3–7. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwAh0">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAh4"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-81-207-4352-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-207-4352-6" id="mwAh8">978-81-207-4352-6</a><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwAiA">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwAiE">2015-09-05</span></span>. <q id="mwAiI">There is a difference between management and manipulation. The difference is thin [...] If management is handling,