</span></li><li about="#cite_note-21" id="cite_note-21"><a href="./Management#cite_ref-21" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-21" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt88" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://archive.org/details/thepsychologyofm16256gut"},"title":{"wt":"The Psychology of Management: The Function of the Mind in Determining, Teaching and Installing Methods of Least Waste"},"first":{"wt":"Lillian Moller"},"last":{"wt":"Gilbreth"},"publisher":{"wt":""},"via":{"wt":"Internet Archive"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApA">Gilbreth, Lillian Moller. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/thepsychologyofm16256gut" id="mwApE"><i id="mwApI">The Psychology of Management: The Function of the Mind in Determining, Teaching and Installing Methods of Least Waste</i></a>  <span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwApM">–</span> via Internet Archive.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Psychology+of+Management%3A+The+Function+of+the+Mind+in+Determining%2C+Teaching+and+Installing+Methods+of+Least+Waste&amp;rft.aulast=Gilbreth&amp;rft.aufirst=Lillian+Moller&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fthepsychologyofm16256gut&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AManagement" class="Z3988" about="#mwt88" id="mwApQ"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt88" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwApU"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-22" id="cite_note-22"><a href="./Management#cite_ref-22" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-22" class="mw-reference-text">
<cite class="citation book" about="#mwt91" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book\n","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last1":{"wt":"Legge"},"first1":{"wt":"David"},"last2":{"wt":"Stanton"},"first2":{"wt":"Pauline"},"last3":{"wt":"Smyth"},"first3":{"wt":"Anne"},"chapter":{"wt":"Learning management (and managing your own learning)"},"editor1-last":{"wt":"Harris"},"editor1-first":{"wt":"Mary G."},"title":{"wt":"Managing Health Services: Concepts and Practice"},"chapter-url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/books?id=yA2SR4DgU5wC"},"location":{"wt":"Marrickville, NSW"},"publisher":{"wt":"Elsevier Australia"},"publication-date":{"wt":"2006"},"page":{"wt":"13"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-7295-3759-9"},"accessdate":{"wt":"2014-07-11"},"quote":{"wt":"The &apos;&apos;manager as bureaucrat&apos;&apos; is the guardian of roles, rules and relationships; his or her style of management relies heavily on working according to the book. In the Weberian tradition managers are necessary to coordinate the different roles that contribute to the production process and to mediate communication from head office to the shop floor and back. This style of management assumes a world view in which bureaucratic role is seen as separate from, and taking precedence over, other constructions of self (including the obligations of citizenship), at least for the duration if the working day."},"date":{"wt":"October 2005"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApY">Legge, David; Stanton, Pauline; Smyth, Anne (October 2005). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=yA2SR4DgU5wC" id="mwApc">"Learning management (and managing your own learning)"</a>.  In Harris, Mary G. <i id="mwApg">Managing Health Services: Concepts and Practice</i>. Marrickville, NSW: Elsevier Australia (published 2006). p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwApk"> </span>13. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwApo">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAps"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-7295-3759-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7295-3759-9" id="mwApw">978-0-7295-3759-9</a><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwAp0">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwAp4">2014-07-11</span></span>. <q id="mwAp8">The <i id="mwAqA">manager as bureaucrat</i> is the guardian of roles, rules and relationships; his or her style of management relies heavily on working according to the book. In the Weberian tradition managers are necessary to coordinate the different roles that contribute to the production process and to mediate communication from head office to the shop floor and back. This style of management assumes a world view in which bureaucratic role is seen as separate from, and taking precedence over, other constructions of self (including the obligations of citizenship), at least for the duration if the working day.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Learning+management+%28and+managing+your+own+learning%29&amp;rft.btitle=Managing+Health+Services%3A+Concepts+and+Practice&amp;rft.place=Marrickville%2C+NSW&amp;rft.pages=13&amp;rft.pub=Elsevier+Australia&amp;rft.date=2005-10&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7295-3759-9&amp;rft.aulast=Legge&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rft.au=Stanton%2C+Pauline&amp;rft.au=Smyth%2C+Anne&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DyA2SR4DgU5wC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AManagement" class="Z3988" about="#mwt91" id="mwAqE"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt91" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwAqI"/>
</span></li><li about="#cite_note-23" id="cite_note-23"><a href="./Management#cite_ref-23" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-23" class="mw-reference-text">Craig, S. (2009, January 29). Merrill Bonus Case Widens as Deal Struggles. <i id="mwAqM">Wall Street Journal</i>. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external autonumber" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123318892645426723" id="mwAqQ"></a>
</span></li><li about="#cite_note-24" id="cite_note-24"><a href="./Management#cite_ref-24" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-24" class="mw-reference-text">
